dical conservatism" contribute to the rise of National Socialism? What roles did they play in the Third Reich? How did their experience of totalitarianism lead them to recast their social and political thought? This biography of Hans Freyer, a prominent German sociologist and political ideologist, is a case study of intellectuals and a "god that failed"--not on the political left, but on the right, where its significance has been overlooked. The author explores the interaction of political ideology and academic social science in democratic and totalitarian regimes, the transformation of German conservatism by the experience of National Socialism, and the ways in which tension between former collaborators and former opponents of National Socialism continued to mold West German intellectual life in the postwar decades.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aConservatismzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aIntellectualszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aNational socialism. 0aRadicalismzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSociologistszGermanyxBiography. 0aSociologyzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAdolf Hitler.  aAntipathy.  aArnold Gehlen.  aBildung.  aBourgeoisie.  aCapitalism.  aCareer.  aCarl Schmitt.  aCommunism.  aContemporary society.  aCriticism.  aCritique.  aDenazification.  aDilthey.  aDisenchantment.  aErnst Forsthoff.  aErnst Troeltsch.  aEthics.  aEthos.  aExplanation.  aFar-right politics.  aFederal republic.  aForeign policy.  aGemeinschaft and Gesellschaft.  aGeorg Simmel.  aGerhard Ritter.  aGermans.  aGleichschaltung.  aHabilitation.  aHans Freyer.  aHans-Georg Gadamer.  aHelmut Schelsky.  aHelmuth Plessner.  aHistoricism.  aHistoriography.  aIdeology.  aInstitution.  aI